WEBVTT

00:27.240 --> 00:29.460
CHAPTER I.

00:30.020 --> 00:33.240
LibriVox Part II.

00:34.700 --> 00:40.220
Most of the luxuries and many of the so-called comforts of life are not only not indispensable,

00:40.700 --> 00:43.720
but positive hindrances to the elevation of mankind.

00:45.160 --> 00:52.280
With respect to luxuries and comforts, the wisest have ever lived a more simple and meager

00:52.280 --> 00:53.600
life than the poor.

00:54.390 --> 01:01.480
The ancient philosophers Chinese, Hindu, Persian, and Greek were a class than which none has

01:01.480 --> 01:07.040
been poorer in outward riches, none so rich in inward.

01:08.240 --> 01:10.000
We know not much about them.

01:10.740 --> 01:14.060
It is remarkable that we know so much of them as we do.

01:15.880 --> 01:20.880
The same is true of the more modern reformers and benefactors of their race.

01:21.780 --> 01:28.240
None can be an impartial or wise observer of human life, but from the vantage ground

01:28.240 --> 01:31.660
of what we should call voluntary poverty.

01:32.880 --> 01:39.280
Of a life of luxury, the fruit is luxury, whether in agriculture or commerce or literature

01:39.280 --> 01:40.320
or art.

01:41.000 --> 01:45.800
There are nowadays professors of philosophy, but not philosophers.

01:46.780 --> 01:51.760
Yet it is admirable to profess because it was once admirable to live.

01:53.500 --> 01:59.340
To be a philosopher is not merely to have subtle thoughts nor even to found a school,

02:00.440 --> 02:09.240
but so to love wisdom as to live according to its dictates a life of simplicity, independence,

02:10.480 --> 02:12.440
magnanimity, and trust.

02:13.140 --> 02:18.500
It is to solve some of the problems of life, not only theoretically but practically.

02:19.580 --> 02:26.080
The success of great scholars and thinkers is commonly a courtier-like success, not kingly,

02:26.440 --> 02:27.880
not manly.

02:29.020 --> 02:35.860
They make shift to live merely by conformity, practically as their fathers did, and are

02:35.860 --> 02:38.760
in no sense the progenitors of a noble race of men.

02:39.440 --> 02:42.160
But why do men degenerate ever?

02:43.200 --> 02:45.200
What makes families run out?

02:45.720 --> 02:51.640
What is the nature of the luxury which innervates and destroys nations?

02:52.960 --> 02:56.380
Are we sure that there is none of it in our own lives?

02:57.540 --> 03:02.820
The philosopher is in advance of his age, even in the outward form of his life.

03:03.770 --> 03:09.580
He is not fed, sheltered, clothed, warmed like his contemporaries.

03:10.300 --> 03:17.500
How can a man be a philosopher and not maintain his vital heat by better methods than other men?

03:18.660 --> 03:26.140
When a man is warmed by the several modes which I have described, what does he want

03:26.140 --> 03:26.660
next?

03:27.430 --> 03:35.020
Surely not more warmth of the same kind, as more and richer food, larger and more splendid

03:35.020 --> 03:41.960
houses, finer and more abundant clothing, more numerous, incessant, and hotter fires,

03:42.280 --> 03:42.980
and the like.

03:43.480 --> 03:50.360
When he has obtained those things which are necessary to life, there is another alternative

03:50.360 --> 03:58.040
than to obtain the superfluities, and that is to adventure on life now, his vacation

03:58.040 --> 04:00.800
from humbler toil having commenced.

04:01.980 --> 04:09.720
The soil, it appears, is suited to the seed, for it has sent its radical downward, and

04:09.720 --> 04:13.820
it may now send its chute upward also with confidence.

04:14.820 --> 04:21.640
Why has man rooted himself thus firmly in the earth, but that he may rise in the same

04:21.640 --> 04:24.040
proportion into the heavens above?

04:25.280 --> 04:32.100
For the nobler plants are valued for the fruit they bear at last in the air and light far

04:32.100 --> 04:39.000
from the ground, and are not treated like the humbler esculents, which, though they

04:39.000 --> 04:45.480
be biennials, and cultivated only till they have perfected their root, and often cut down

04:45.480 --> 04:50.960
atop for this purpose, so that most would not know them in their flowering season.

04:52.100 --> 04:58.660
I do not mean to prescribe rules to strong and valiant natures who will mind their own

04:58.660 --> 05:06.040
affairs whether in heaven or hell, and perchance build more magnificently and spend more lavishly

05:06.040 --> 05:12.180
than the richest, without ever impoverishing themselves, not knowing how they live, if

05:12.180 --> 05:18.480
indeed there are any such as has been dreamed, nor to those who find their encouragement

05:18.480 --> 05:24.760
and inspiration in precisely the present condition of things, and cherish it with the fondness

05:24.760 --> 05:26.360
and enthusiasm of lovers.

05:27.300 --> 05:31.060
And, to some extent, I reckon myself in this number.

05:31.440 --> 05:37.720
I do not speak to those who are well employed in whatever circumstances, and they know whether

05:37.720 --> 05:39.540
they are well employed or not.

05:40.320 --> 05:48.280
But mainly to the mass of men who are discontented, and idly complaining of the hardness of their

05:48.280 --> 05:55.860
lot or of the times, when they might improve them, there are some who complain most energetically

05:55.860 --> 06:04.380
and inconsolably of any, because they are, as they say, doing their duty.

06:05.320 --> 06:12.580
I also have in mind that seemingly wealthy, but most terribly impoverished class of all,

06:13.040 --> 06:19.300
who have accumulated dross, but know not how to use it or get rid of it, and thus have

06:19.300 --> 06:23.540
forged their own golden or silver fetters.

06:24.220 --> 06:30.900
If I should attempt to tell how I have desired to spend my life in years past, it would probably

06:30.900 --> 06:34.940
surprise those of my readers who are somewhat acquainted with its actual history.

06:35.840 --> 06:39.720
It would certainly astonish those who know nothing about it.

06:40.240 --> 06:43.640
I will only hint at some of the enterprises which I have cherished.

06:44.720 --> 06:50.380
In any weather, at any hour of the day or night, I have been anxious to improve the

06:50.380 --> 06:57.420
knick of time, and notch it on my stick, too, to stand on the meeting of two eternities,

06:57.860 --> 07:05.020
the past and future, which is precisely the present moment, to toe that line.

07:06.080 --> 07:11.200
You will pardon some obscurities, for there are more secrets in my trade than in most

07:11.200 --> 07:17.380
men's, and yet not voluntarily kept, but inseparable from its very nature.

07:17.920 --> 07:24.200
I would gladly tell all that I know about it, and never paint no admittance on my gate.

07:25.320 --> 07:32.900
I long ago lost a hound, a bay horse, and a turtle dove, and am still on their trail.

07:33.620 --> 07:38.400
Many are the travelers I have spoken concerning them, describing their tracks and what calls

07:38.400 --> 07:39.520
they answered to.

07:39.820 --> 07:46.900
I have met one or two who had heard the hound and the tramp of the horse, and even seen

07:46.900 --> 07:51.780
the dove disappear behind a cloud, and they seemed as anxious to recover them as if they

07:51.780 --> 07:53.320
had lost them themselves.

07:54.520 --> 08:01.780
To anticipate not the sunrise and the dawn merely, but if possible nature herself.

08:02.620 --> 08:08.920
How many mornings, summer and winter, before yet any neighbor was stirring about his business,

08:09.300 --> 08:10.480
have I been about mine?

08:11.280 --> 08:17.920
No doubt many of my townsmen have met me returning from this enterprise, farmers starting for

08:17.920 --> 08:21.460
Boston in the twilight, or woodchoppers going to their work.

08:22.560 --> 08:30.420
It is true I never assisted the sun materially in his rising, but doubt not it was of the

08:30.420 --> 08:33.480
last importance only to be present at it.

08:34.200 --> 08:41.640
So many autumn days and winter days spent outside the town, trying to hear what was

08:41.640 --> 08:44.920
in the wind, to hear and carry it express.

08:46.420 --> 08:53.000
I well-nigh sunk all my capital in it, and lost my own breath into the bargain running

08:53.000 --> 08:54.380
in the face of it.

08:55.140 --> 09:01.220
If it had concerned either of the political parties, depend upon it, it would have appeared

09:01.220 --> 09:04.300
in the Gazette with the earliest intelligence.

09:05.120 --> 09:11.620
At other times, watching from the observatory of some cliff or tree to telegraph any new

09:11.620 --> 09:18.280
arrival, or waiting at evening on the hilltops for the sky to fall, that I might catch something,

09:18.980 --> 09:25.780
though I never caught much, and that, mana-wise, would dissolve again in the sun.

09:26.500 --> 09:33.720
For a long time I was reporter to a journal, of no very wide circulation, whose editor

09:33.720 --> 09:40.120
has never yet seen fit to print the bulk of my contributions, and, as is too common with

09:40.120 --> 09:44.080
writers, I got only my labor for my pains.

09:45.080 --> 09:49.280
However, in this case my pains were their own reward.

09:50.120 --> 09:58.220
For many years I was self-appointed inspector of snow-storms and rain-storms, and did my

09:58.220 --> 10:07.080
duty faithfully, surveyor, if not of highways, then of forest paths, and all across lot routes,

10:07.700 --> 10:13.620
keeping them open, and ravines, bridged and passable at all seasons, where the public

10:13.620 --> 10:15.740
heel had testified to their utility.

10:16.480 --> 10:23.380
I have looked after the wild stock of the town, which give a faithful herdsman a good

10:23.380 --> 10:30.840
deal of trouble by leaping fences, and I have had an eye to the unfrequented nooks and corners

10:30.840 --> 10:36.960
of the farm, though I did not always know whether Jonas or Solomon worked in a particular

10:36.960 --> 10:39.540
field today, that was none of my business.

10:40.200 --> 10:47.640
I have watered the red huckleberry, the sand cherry and the nettle tree, the red pine and

10:47.640 --> 10:53.980
the black ash, the white grape and the yellow violet, which might have withered else in

10:53.980 --> 10:54.740
dry seasons.

10:56.060 --> 11:02.660
In short, I went on thus for a long time, I may say it without boasting, faithfully

11:02.660 --> 11:08.800
minding my business, till it became more and more evident that my townsman would not, after

11:08.800 --> 11:15.020
all, admit me into the list of town officers, nor make my place a sinishure with a moderate

11:15.020 --> 11:15.520
allowance.

11:16.300 --> 11:22.760
My accounts, which I can swear to have kept faithfully, I have indeed never got audited,

11:23.200 --> 11:30.360
still less accepted, still less paid and settled, however I have not set my heart on that.

11:31.480 --> 11:36.820
Not long since a strolling Indian went to sell baskets at the house of a well-known

11:36.820 --> 11:37.860
lawyer in my neighborhood.

11:39.120 --> 11:42.020
"'Do you wish to buy any baskets?' he asked.

11:43.040 --> 11:45.980
"'No, we do not want any,' was the reply.

11:47.100 --> 11:49.740
"'What?' exclaimed the Indian as he went out the gate.

11:50.020 --> 11:52.940
"'Do you mean to starve us?'

11:53.340 --> 11:59.080
Having seen his industrious white neighbors so well off that the lawyer had only to weave

11:59.080 --> 12:05.660
arguments and by some magic wealth and standing followed, he had said to himself, I will go

12:05.660 --> 12:12.340
into business, I will weave baskets, it is a thing which I can do,' thinking that when

12:12.340 --> 12:17.960
he had made the baskets he would have done his part, and then it would be the white man's

12:17.960 --> 12:18.840
to buy them.

12:19.580 --> 12:25.720
He had not discovered that it was necessary for him to make it worth the other's while

12:25.720 --> 12:33.000
to buy them, or at least make him think that it was so, or to make something else which

12:33.000 --> 12:34.960
would be worth his while to buy.

12:36.080 --> 12:44.060
I too had woven a kind of basket of a delicate texture, but I had not made it worth anyone's

12:44.060 --> 12:45.420
while to buy them.

12:46.280 --> 12:53.580
Yet not the less in my case did I think it worth my while to weave them, and instead

12:53.580 --> 13:00.200
of studying how to make it worth men's while to buy my baskets, I studied rather how to

13:00.200 --> 13:02.180
avoid the necessity of selling them.

13:02.900 --> 13:09.100
The life which men praise and regard as successful is but one kind.

13:09.760 --> 13:14.120
Why should we exaggerate any one kind at the expense of the others?

13:15.540 --> 13:22.380
Finding that my fellow citizens were not likely to offer me any room in the courthouse or

13:22.380 --> 13:28.600
any curacy or living anywhere else, but I must shift for myself.

13:29.300 --> 13:35.240
I turned my face more exclusively than ever to the woods, where I was better known.

13:36.040 --> 13:41.680
I determined to go into business at once, and not wait to acquire the usual capital,

13:42.320 --> 13:45.480
using such slender means as I had already got.

13:46.540 --> 13:53.420
My purpose in going to Walden Pond was not to live cheaply, nor to live dearly there,

13:53.800 --> 13:59.340
but to transact some private business with the fewest obstacles.

14:00.520 --> 14:06.860
To be hindered from accomplishing which for want of a little common sense, a little enterprise

14:06.860 --> 14:11.440
and business talent appeared not so sad as foolish.

14:12.980 --> 14:16.100
I have always endeavored to acquire strict business habits.

14:16.660 --> 14:18.860
They are indispensable to every man.

14:19.340 --> 14:26.280
If your trade is with the celestial empire, then some small counting-house on the coast,

14:26.640 --> 14:29.360
in some Salem harbor, will be fixture enough.

14:30.180 --> 14:36.300
You will export such articles as the country affords—purely native products, much ice

14:36.300 --> 14:40.420
and pine timber and a little granite, always in native bottoms.

14:41.180 --> 14:42.720
These will be good ventures.

14:43.340 --> 14:49.160
To oversee all the details yourself in person, to be at once pilot and captain and owner

14:49.160 --> 14:54.800
and underwriter, to buy and sell and keep the accounts, to read every letter received

14:54.800 --> 15:01.040
and write or read every letter sent, to superintend the discharge of imports night and day, to

15:01.040 --> 15:07.200
be upon many parts of the coast almost at the same time—often the richest freight

15:07.200 --> 15:12.860
will be discharged upon a Jersey shore—to be your own telegraph, unweariedly sweeping

15:12.860 --> 15:18.980
the horizon, speaking all passing vessels bound coast-wise, to keep up a steady dispatch

15:18.980 --> 15:24.900
of commodities for the supply of such a distant and exorbitant market, to keep yourself informed

15:24.900 --> 15:30.460
of the state of the markets, prospects of war and peace everywhere, and anticipate the

15:30.460 --> 15:32.380
tendencies of trade and civilization.

15:33.080 --> 15:39.760
Taking advantage of the results of all exploring expeditions, using new passages and all improvements

15:39.760 --> 15:46.960
in navigation, charts to be studied, the position of reefs and new lights and buoys to be ascertained,

15:46.960 --> 15:54.100
and ever and ever the logarithmic tables to be corrected, for by the error of some calculator

15:54.100 --> 16:01.220
the vessel often splits upon a rock that should have reached a friendly pier, there is the

16:01.220 --> 16:08.980
told fate of La Prusse, universal science to be kept pace with, studying the lives of

16:08.980 --> 16:14.660
all great discoverers and navigators, great adventurers and merchants, from Hanno and

16:14.660 --> 16:20.300
the Phoenicians down to our day, in fine account of stock to be taken from time to time to

16:20.300 --> 16:26.900
know how you stand. It is a labor to task the faculties of a man, such problems of profit

16:26.900 --> 16:33.760
and loss of interest of tear and tread, engaging of all kinds in it, as demand a universal

16:33.760 --> 16:41.940
knowledge. I have thought that Walden Pond would be a good place for business. Not solely

16:41.940 --> 16:48.140
on account of the railroad and the ice trade, it offers advantages which it may not be good

16:48.140 --> 16:58.480
to divulge. It is a good port and a good foundation. No Neva marshes to be filled, though you must

16:58.480 --> 17:05.100
everywhere build on piles of your own driving. It is said that a flood tide with a westerly

17:05.100 --> 17:12.480
wind and ice in the Neva would sweep St. Petersburg from the face of the earth. As this business

17:12.480 --> 17:19.420
was to be entered into without the usual capital, it may not be easy to conjecture where those

17:19.420 --> 17:24.680
means that will still be indispensable to every such undertaking were to be obtained.

17:25.900 --> 17:32.680
As for clothing, to come at once to the practical part of the question, perhaps we are led oftener

17:32.680 --> 17:39.780
by the love of novelty and a regard for the opinions of men in procuring it than by a

17:39.780 --> 17:48.380
true utility. Let him who has work to do recollect that the object of clothing is, first, to

17:48.380 --> 17:55.860
retain the vital heat, and secondly, in this state of society, to cover nakedness, and

17:55.860 --> 18:01.060
he may judge how much of any necessary or important work may be accomplished without

18:01.060 --> 18:08.360
adding to his wardrobe. Kings and queens who wear a suit but once, though made by some

18:08.360 --> 18:13.800
tailor or dressmaker to their majesties, cannot know the comfort of wearing a suit

18:13.800 --> 18:21.160
that fits. They are no better than wooden horses to hang the clean clothes on. Every

18:21.160 --> 18:29.120
day our garments become more assimilated to ourselves, receiving the impress of the wearer's

18:29.120 --> 18:34.600
character until we hesitate to lay them aside without such delay and medical appliances

18:34.600 --> 18:42.360
and some such solemnity even as our bodies. No man ever stood the lower in my estimation

18:42.360 --> 18:49.040
for having a patch in his clothes, yet I am sure that there is greater anxiety commonly

18:49.040 --> 18:56.180
to have fashionable or at least clean and unpatched clothes than to have a sound conscience.

18:56.980 --> 19:06.980
But even if the rent is not mended, perhaps the worst vice betrayed is improvidence. I

19:06.980 --> 19:14.120
sometimes try my acquaintances by such tests as this. Who could wear a patch or two extra

19:14.120 --> 19:20.260
seams only over the knee? Most behave as if they believed that their prospects for life

19:20.260 --> 19:25.640
would be ruined if they should do it. It would be easier for them to hobble to town with

19:25.640 --> 19:32.260
a broken leg than with a broken pantaloon. Often if an accident happens to a gentleman's

19:32.260 --> 19:38.900
legs they can be mended, but if a similar accident happens to the legs of his pantaloons

19:39.340 --> 19:45.900
there is no help for it, for he considers not what is truly respectable, but what is

19:46.380 --> 19:55.260
respected. We know but few men, a great many coats and breeches. Dress a scarecrow in your

19:55.260 --> 20:03.300
latest shift, you standing shiftless by. Who would not soonest salute the scarecrow? Passing

20:03.300 --> 20:08.840
a cornfield the other day, close by a hat and coat on a stake, I recognized the owner

20:08.840 --> 20:15.300
of the farm. He was only a little more weather-beaten than when I saw him last. I have heard of

20:15.300 --> 20:21.780
a dog that barked at every stranger who approached his master's premises with clothes on, but

20:21.780 --> 20:29.120
as easily quieted by a naked thief. It is an interesting question how far men would

20:29.120 --> 20:37.260
retain their relative rank if they were divested of their clothes. Could you, in such a case,

20:37.880 --> 20:43.780
tell surely of any company of civilized men which belonged to the most respected class?

20:44.160 --> 20:50.940
When Madame Pfeiffer, in her adventurous travels round the world from east to west, had got

20:50.940 --> 20:57.200
so near home as Asiatic Russia, she says that she felt the necessity of wearing other than

20:57.200 --> 21:03.260
a traveling dress when she went to meet the authorities, for she was now in a civilized

21:03.260 --> 21:11.100
country where people are judged by their clothes. Even in our democratic New England towns the

21:11.100 --> 21:17.980
accidental possession of wealth, and its manifestation in dress and equipage alone, obtained for

21:17.980 --> 21:24.720
the possessor almost universal respect. But they yield such respect, numerous as they

21:24.720 --> 21:33.880
are, are so far heathen, and need to have a missionary sent to them. Besides, clothes

21:33.880 --> 21:39.940
introduced sewing, a kind of work which you may call endless. A woman's dress, at least,

21:40.240 --> 21:47.740
is never done. A man who has at length found something to do will not need to get a new

21:47.740 --> 21:56.260
suit to do it in. For him the old will do, that has lain dusty in the garret for an

21:56.260 --> 22:02.720
indeterminate period. Old shoes will serve a hero longer than they have served his valet,

22:02.940 --> 22:10.100
if a hero ever has a valet. Bare feet are older than shoes, and he can make them do.

22:10.880 --> 22:18.900
Only those who go to soirees and legislative balls must have new coats. Coats, too, change

22:18.900 --> 22:24.980
as often as the man changes in them. But if my jacket and trousers, my hat and shoes,

22:25.480 --> 22:37.740
are fit to worship God in, they will do, will they not? Whoever saw his old clothes, his

22:37.740 --> 22:43.260
primitive elements, so that it was not a deed of charity to bestow it on some poor boy?

22:43.940 --> 22:50.920
By him perchance to be bestowed on some poorer still? Or shall we say richer? Who could do

22:50.920 --> 22:59.720
with less? I say, beware of all enterprises that require new clothes, and not rather a

22:59.720 --> 23:07.180
new wearer of clothes. If there is not a new man, how can the new clothes be made to fit?

23:07.740 --> 23:15.760
If you have any enterprise before you, try it in your old clothes. All men want not something

23:15.760 --> 23:22.860
to do with, but something to do, or rather something to be. Perhaps we should never procure

23:22.860 --> 23:29.760
a new suit, however ragged or dirty the old, until we have so conducted, so enterprised,

23:30.180 --> 23:36.900
or sailed in some way, that we feel like new men in the old, and that to retain it would

23:36.900 --> 23:44.820
be like keeping new wine in old bottles. Our molting season, like that of the fowls, must

23:44.820 --> 23:51.740
be a crisis in our lives. The loon retires to solitary ponds to spend it. Thus also the

23:51.740 --> 23:58.780
snake casts its slough, and the caterpillar its wormy coat, by an internal industry and

23:58.780 --> 24:06.460
expansion, for clothes are but our outmost cuticle and mortal coil. Otherwise we shall

24:06.460 --> 24:12.800
be found sailing under false colors, and be inevitably cashiered at last by our own opinion,

24:13.200 --> 24:20.660
as well as that of mankind. We don garment after garment, as if we grew like exogenous

24:20.660 --> 24:29.680
plants by addition without. Our outside and often thin and fanciful clothes are our epidermis,

24:29.880 --> 24:35.800
our false skin, which partakes not of our life, and may be stripped off here and there

24:35.800 --> 24:42.360
without fatal injury. Our thicker garments, constantly worn, are our cellular integument,

24:42.840 --> 24:50.920
or cortex. But our shirts are our lieber, or true bark, which cannot be removed without

24:50.920 --> 24:57.580
girdling, and so destroying the man. I believe that all races at some seasons wear something

24:57.580 --> 25:04.080
equivalent to the shirt. It is desirable that a man be clad so simply that he can lay his

25:04.080 --> 25:11.200
hands on himself in the dark, and that he live in all respect so compactly and preparedly

25:11.200 --> 25:17.380
that, if an enemy take the town, he can, like the old philosopher, walk out the gate empty-handed

25:17.380 --> 25:25.540
without anxiety. While one thick garment is, for most purposes, as good as three thin ones,

25:25.940 --> 25:32.480
and cheap clothing can be obtained at prices really to suit customers, while a thick coat

25:32.480 --> 25:38.640
can be bought for five dollars, which will last as many years, thick pantaloons for two

25:38.640 --> 25:44.140
dollars, cowhide boots for a dollar and a half a pair, a summer hat for a quarter of

25:44.140 --> 25:51.100
a dollar, and a winter cap for sixty-two and a half cents, or a better be made at home

25:51.100 --> 25:57.960
at a nominal cost, where is he so poor that, clad in such a suit of his own earning, there

25:57.960 --> 26:05.500
will not be found wise men to do him reverence. When I ask for a garment of a particular form,

26:05.960 --> 26:13.320
my tailoress tells me gravely, They do not make them so now, not emphasizing the they

26:13.320 --> 26:20.320
at all, as if she quoted an authority as impersonal as the fates, and I find it difficult to get

26:20.320 --> 26:26.660
what I want, simply because she cannot believe that I mean what I say, that I am so rash.

26:27.260 --> 26:34.260
When I hear this oracular sentence, I am for a moment absorbed in thought, emphasizing

26:34.260 --> 26:40.120
to myself each word separately that I may come at the meaning of it, that I may find

26:40.120 --> 26:47.740
out by what degree of consanguinity they are related to me, and what authority they may

26:47.740 --> 26:55.360
have in an affair which affects me so nearly, and finally I am inclined to answer her with

26:55.360 --> 27:04.200
equal mystery, and without any more emphasis of the they. It is true, they did not make

27:04.200 --> 27:13.360
them so recently, but they do now. Of what use this measuring of me if she does not measure

27:13.360 --> 27:20.920
my character, but only the breadth of my shoulders, as it were a peg to bang the coat on? We worship

27:20.920 --> 27:29.700
not the graces, nor the parse, but fashion. She spins and weaves and cuts with full authority.

27:30.460 --> 27:35.180
The head monkey at Paris puts on a traveler's cap, and all the monkeys in America do the

27:35.180 --> 27:42.120
same. I sometimes despair of getting anything quite simple and honest adone in this world

27:42.120 --> 27:49.360
by the help of men. They would have to be passed through a powerful press first to squeeze

27:49.360 --> 27:56.040
their old notions out of them so that they would not so soon get upon their legs again,

27:56.420 --> 28:02.780
and then there would be someone in the company with a maggot in his head hatched from an

28:02.780 --> 28:09.300
egg deposited there nobody knows when, for not even fire kills these things, and you

28:09.300 --> 28:15.320
would have lost your labor. Nevertheless we will not forget that some Egyptian wheat was

28:15.320 --> 28:17.460
handed down to us by a mummy.

28:18.660 --> 28:25.320
On the whole I think that it cannot be maintained that dressing has in this or any country risen

28:25.320 --> 28:32.660
to the dignity of an art. At present men make shift to wear what they can get. Like shipwrecked

28:32.660 --> 28:36.860
sailors they put on what they can find on the beach, and at a little distance, whether

28:36.860 --> 28:43.540
of space or time, laugh at each other's masquerade. Every generation laughs at the old fashions,

28:43.540 --> 28:45.960
but follows religiously the new.

28:46.680 --> 28:53.020
We are amused at beholding the costume of Henry VIII or Queen Elizabeth as much as if

28:53.020 --> 28:59.720
it was that of the King and Queen of the Cannibal Islands. All costume off a man is pitiful

28:59.720 --> 29:08.040
or grotesque. It is only the serious eye peering from and the sincere life past within it which

29:08.040 --> 29:14.440
restrain laughter and consecrate the costume of any people. Let Harlequin be taken with

29:14.440 --> 29:21.580
a fit of the colic, and his trappings will have to serve that mood too. When the soldier

29:21.580 --> 29:26.680
is hit by a cannonball rags are as becoming as purple.

29:27.960 --> 29:35.000
The childish and savage taste of men and women for new patterns keeps how many shaking and

29:35.000 --> 29:40.380
winting through kaleidoscopes that they may discover the particular figure which this

29:40.380 --> 29:46.500
generation requires today. The manufacturers have learned that this taste is merely whimsical.

29:47.420 --> 29:52.440
Of two patterns which differ only by a few threads more or less of a particular color,

29:53.020 --> 29:58.640
the one will be sold readily, the other lie on the shelf, though it frequently happens

29:58.640 --> 30:03.900
that after the lapse of a season the latter becomes the more fashionable. Comparatively,

30:04.580 --> 30:10.860
tattooing is not the hideous custom which it is called. It is not barbarous merely because

30:10.860 --> 30:18.080
the printing is skin deep and unalterable. I cannot believe that our factory system is

30:18.080 --> 30:24.780
the best mode by which men may get clothing. The condition of the operatives is becoming

30:24.780 --> 30:31.060
every day more like that of the English, and it cannot be wondered at, since, as far as

30:31.060 --> 30:38.240
I have heard or observed, the principal object is not that mankind may be well and honestly

30:38.240 --> 30:48.400
clad, but unquestionably that corporations may be enriched. In the long run men hit only

30:48.400 --> 30:55.400
what they aim at. Therefore, though they should fail immediately, they had better aim at something

30:55.400 --> 30:55.960
high.

30:57.920 --> 31:06.020
As for a shelter, I will not deny that this is now a necessary of life, though there are

31:06.020 --> 31:11.040
instances of men having done without it for long periods in colder countries than this.

31:12.400 --> 31:19.400
Samuel Lang says that, quote, the laplander in his skin dress and in a skin bag which

31:19.400 --> 31:26.420
he puts over his head and shoulders will sleep night after night on the snow, in a degree

31:26.420 --> 31:31.720
of cold which would extinguish the life of one exposed to it in any woollen clothing.

31:33.760 --> 31:42.000
He had seen them asleep thus, yet he adds, quote, they are not hardier than other people,

31:42.280 --> 31:47.940
end quote. But probably the man did not live long on the earth without discovering the

31:47.940 --> 31:54.460
convenience which there is in a house, the domestic comforts, which phrase may have originally

31:54.460 --> 32:01.100
signified the satisfactions of the house more than of the family, though these must be extremely

32:01.100 --> 32:05.620
partial and occasional in those climates where the house is associated in our thoughts with

32:05.620 --> 32:14.020
winter, or the rainy season chiefly, and two-thirds of the year, except for a parasol, is unnecessary.

32:15.000 --> 32:22.440
In our climate, in the summer, it was formerly almost solely a covering at night. In the

32:22.440 --> 32:28.740
Indian Gazettes a wigwam was the symbol of a day's march, and a row of them, cut or painted

32:28.740 --> 32:35.560
on the bark of a tree, signified that so many times they had camped. Man was not made so

32:35.560 --> 32:41.680
large-limbed and robust, but that he must seek to narrow his world and wall in a space

32:41.680 --> 32:49.380
such as fitted him. He was at first bare and out of doors, but though this was pleasant

32:49.380 --> 32:55.660
enough in serene and warm weather, by daylight, the rainy season and the winter, to say nothing

32:55.660 --> 33:02.140
of the torrid sun, would perhaps have nipped his race in the bud if he had not made haste

33:02.140 --> 33:08.300
to clothe himself with the shelter of a house. Adam and Eve, according to the fable, wore

33:08.300 --> 33:15.960
the bower before other clothes. Man wanted a home, a place of warmth or comfort, first

33:15.960 --> 33:24.520
of warmth, then the warmth of the affections. We may imagine a time when, in the infancy

33:24.520 --> 33:30.660
of the human race, some enterprising mortal crept into a hollow in a rock for shelter.

33:31.720 --> 33:37.380
Every child begins the world again to some extent, and loves to stay outdoors even in

33:37.380 --> 33:44.580
wet and cold. It plays house as well as horse, having an instinct for it. Who does not remember

33:44.580 --> 33:50.920
the interest with which, when young, he looked at shelving rocks or any approach to a cave?

33:51.580 --> 33:57.660
It was the natural yearning of that portion, any portion of our most primitive ancestor

33:57.660 --> 34:04.040
which still survived in us. From the cave we have advanced to roofs of palm leaves,

34:04.040 --> 34:11.840
of bark and boughs, of linen woven and stretched, of grass and straw, of boards and shingles,

34:12.100 --> 34:19.100
of stones and tiles. At last we know not what it is to live in the open air, and our lives

34:19.100 --> 34:25.620
are domestic in more senses than we think. From the hearth the field is a great distance.

34:26.360 --> 34:32.360
It would be well, perhaps, if we were to spend more of our days and nights without any obstruction

34:32.360 --> 34:38.640
between us and the celestial bodies, if the poet did not speak so much from under a roof,

34:39.220 --> 34:47.540
or the saint dwell there so long. Birds do not sing in caves, nor do doves cherish their

34:47.540 --> 34:55.540
innocence in dovecots. However, if one designs to construct a dwelling-house, it behooves

34:55.540 --> 35:02.260
him to exercise a little Yankee shrewdness, lest, after all, he find himself in a work-house,

35:02.700 --> 35:10.720
a labyrinth without a clue, a museum, an alms-house, a prison, or a splendid mausoleum instead.

35:12.160 --> 35:19.560
Consider first how slight a shelter is absolutely necessary. I have seen Penobscot Indians in

35:19.560 --> 35:26.300
this town living in tents of thin cotton cloth while the snow was nearly a foot deep around

35:26.300 --> 35:34.080
them, and I thought that they would be glad to have it deeper to keep out the wind. Formerly,

35:34.320 --> 35:40.180
when how to get my living honestly, with freedom left for my proper pursuits, was a question

35:40.180 --> 35:46.020
which vexed me even more than it does now, for unfortunately I am become somewhat callous.

35:46.020 --> 35:52.940
I used to see a large box by the railroad, six feet long by three wide, in which the

35:52.940 --> 35:59.140
laborers locked up their tools at night, and it suggested to me that every man who has

35:59.140 --> 36:06.640
hard pushed might get such a one for a dollar, and having bored a few auger-holes in it,

36:06.780 --> 36:12.500
to admit the air at least, get into it when it rained and at night, and hook down the

36:12.500 --> 36:19.860
lid, and so have freedom in his love, and in his soul be free. This did not appear the

36:19.860 --> 36:26.480
worst, nor by any means a despicable alternative. You could sit up as late as you pleased, and

36:26.480 --> 36:32.340
whenever you got up go abroad without any landlord or house-lord dogging you for rent.

36:33.460 --> 36:40.040
Many a man is harassed to death to pay the rent of a larger and more luxurious box, who

36:40.040 --> 36:46.720
would not have frozen to death in such a box as this. I am far from jesting. Economy

36:46.720 --> 36:53.620
is a subject which admits of being treated with levity, but I cannot so be disposed of.

36:54.520 --> 37:00.800
A comfortable house for a rude and hardy race, that lived mostly out of doors, was once made

37:00.800 --> 37:07.860
here almost entirely of such materials as nature furnished ready to their hands. Gukin,

37:08.130 --> 37:15.160
who was superintendent of the Indians, subject to the Massachusetts colony, writing in 1674,

37:16.020 --> 37:22.020
says, The best of their houses are covered very neatly, tight and warm, with barks of

37:22.020 --> 37:28.140
trees, slipped from their bodies at those seasons when the sap is up, and made into

37:28.140 --> 37:35.140
great flakes, with pressure of weighty timber, when they are green. The meaner sort are covered

37:35.140 --> 37:41.420
with mats, which they make of a kind of bulrush, and are also indifferently tight and warm,

37:41.800 --> 37:48.540
but not so good as the former. Some I have seen sixty or a hundred feet long and thirty

37:48.540 --> 37:55.080
feet broad. I have often lodged in their wigwams, and found them as warm as the best English

37:55.080 --> 38:04.400
houses. He adds that they were commonly carpeted and lined within with well-wrought embroidered

38:04.400 --> 38:11.360
mats, and were furnished with various utensils. The Indians had advanced so far as to regulate

38:11.360 --> 38:16.940
the effect of the wind by a mat suspended over the hole in the roof and moved by a string.

38:17.720 --> 38:23.580
Such a lodge was in the first instance constructed in a day or two at most, and taken down and

38:23.580 --> 38:29.140
put up in a few hours, and every family owned one, or its apartment in one.

